measurement of population and the implications of population growth for all inhabitants of Earth.&nbsp; South Asia is one of Earth&rsquo;s most populous geographic regions.&nbsp; Population of a region, realm, or nation provides some information, but a more important statistic is that of <em>population density</em>, or the number of people per unit area (such as a square kilometer or square mile).&nbsp; Population density, calculated arithmetically to report the number of people per unit area can be deceptive.&nbsp; Vast parts of a measured area may not be suitable to sustain life, while other areas, for a variety of reasons, encourage human habitation.&nbsp; For example, river valleys of South Asia support crowded villages, while desert and mountain areas have few inhabitants.&nbsp; A more realistic appraisal of population density is achieved by calculating <em>physiologic density</em>, or the number of inhabitants per unit of arable land (land suitable for farming).&nbsp; This calculation offers students of population a more realistic depiction of resources available per person.&nbsp;</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","headerText":"Understanding complex
